# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baseball-glove
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:baseball-glove/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:baseball-glove/1920-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1920 throughout the world.
[src:baseball-glove/1920-in-baseball] All Negro leagues standings below are per MLB and Seamheads.
[src:baseball-glove/1920-in-baseball] This was the first season of organized Negro league baseball.
[src:baseball-glove/1920-in-baseball] The first Negro National League would run for the next decade and is considered to be of major league status.
[src:baseball-glove/1920-in-baseball] The Chicago American Giants, managed by league founder and former player Rube Foster, won the first league pennant.
[src:baseball-glove/1920-in-baseball] A loose confederation of teams were gathered in the East to compete with the West, however East teams did not organize a formal league as the West did.
[src:baseball-glove/1954-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1954 throughout the world.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] The first series of gloves were released in 1998 under the name "Academy".
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] In 2000 the company experienced rapid growth when it changed its name to Akadema, moved into the old Yoo-hoo factory in Garfield, NJ, and released the patented Reptilian Glove.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] Akadema signed Ozzie Smith as the company spokesman and then Anthony Telford and Clay Bellinger became the first Major League Players endorsing Akadema.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] Kris Totten (a former Minor League player for the Seattle Mariners) joined the firm to head up sales.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] The company would follow up the Reptilian with the Claw, The Funnel and Spiral Lock, Tacktion Grip, The Hot Hands and the UFO Mitt to continue the companies first decade in creative sports design.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] The most popular of the patented glove however has been the Praying Mantis Mitt which was created with input from Gary Carter.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] The company crossed over into popular culture when their products appeared in Adam Sandler films such as *Click*, *Benchwarmers* and the Billy Bob Thornton remake of *Bad News Bears*.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] Akadema also has been a sponsor of Spike TV programs "Pros vs Joes" and "DEA" second season.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] Akadema's most important and visible endorsement deals have been the signing of Manny Ramirez from 2004 to 2011 and a five-year deal with future star Bryce Harper.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] Shane Victorino has won three Gold Glove Award trophies since signing on with Akadema.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] Akadema's other current endorsements are with: Bobby Jenks, Brandon Moss, Jose Veras, Tim Redding, Mark Melancon, Vin Mazzaro, Ross Ohlendorf, Vicente Padilla, Brandon McCarthy, Darnell McDonald, Derek Holland, Willie Eyre, Cameron Maybin, and Craig Breslow.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] Akadema also became strong within the women's fast pitch market.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] They have sponsored Crystl Bustos 2000-2010 and Monica Abbott of Team USA 2008-2010 and are an official supplier to USA softball Olympic team and the National Pro Fast Pitch League.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] As the pro ranks grew, the Akadema brand spread quickly and became very popular among Minor League and college level players.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] In addition to modern gloves, Akadema introduced the Hoboken Collection, a vintage line of equipment that had been used by Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Bob Feller, Dazzy Vance, Mickey Cochrane and Yogi Berra.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] Akadema quickly gained rights to Ken-Wel and Reach companies trademarks.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] Akadema started manufacturing through suppliers overseas but unlike most manufacturers of the day, Akadema has brought some manufacturing in house to the USA.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] Akadema started its own wood baseball bat shop and can customize a bat.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] In 2008 the company purchased an industrial building and consolidated its operations under one roof in Hawthorne, NJ.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] According to *Inc. magazine*, 2007 sales were 4.8 million.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] Current sales are said to be around seven million.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] In 2010, the company opened its own embroidery shop.
[src:baseball-glove/akadema] That same year the company started its own baseball glove shop making it one of the few companies that still makes wood bats, metal bats and gloves in the USA.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] After his retirement as a player, Spalding remained active with the Chicago White Stockings as president and part-owner.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] In the 1880s, he took players on the first world tour of baseball.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] With William Hulbert, Spalding organized the National League.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] He later called for the commission that investigated the origins of baseball and falsely credited Abner Doubleday with creating the game.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] As of the 2026 season, Spalding holds the individual records for the fewest career home runs per nine innings (0.0468) and the highest career winning percentage (.794).
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Having played baseball throughout his youth, Spalding first played competitively with the Rockford Pioneers, a youth team, which he joined in 1865.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] After pitching his team to a 26–2 victory over a local men's amateur team (the Mercantiles), he was approached at the age of 15 by the Rockford Forest Citys, for whom he played for five years.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] William Hulbert, principal owner of the Chicago White Stockings, did not like the loose organization of the National Association and the gambling element that influenced it, so he decided to create a new organization, which he dubbed the National League of Baseball Clubs.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] To aid him in this venture, Hulbert enlisted the help of Spalding.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Playing to the pitcher's desire to return to his Midwestern roots and challenging Spalding's integrity, Hulbert convinced Spalding to sign a contract to play for the White Stockings (now known as the Chicago Cubs) in 1876.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Spalding then coaxed teammates Deacon White, Ross Barnes and Cal McVey, as well as Philadelphia Athletics players Cap Anson and Bob Addy, to sign with Chicago.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] This was all done under complete secrecy during the playing season because players were all free agents in those days and they did not want their current club and especially the fans to know they were leaving to play elsewhere the next year.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] News of the signings by the Boston and Philadelphia players leaked to the press before the season ended and all of them faced verbal abuse and physical threats from the fans of those cities.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] He was "the premier pitcher of the 1870s", leading the league in victories for each of his six full seasons as a professional.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] During each of those years he was his team's only pitcher.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] In 1876, Spalding won 47 games as the prime pitcher for the White Stockings and led them to win the first-ever National League pennant by a wide margin.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] In 1877, Spalding began to use a glove to protect his catching hand.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] People had used gloves previously, but they were not popular, and Spalding himself was skeptical of wearing one at first.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] However, once he began donning gloves, he influenced other players to do so.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Spalding retired from playing baseball in 1878 at the age of 27, although he continued as president and part owner of the White Stockings and a major influence on the National League.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Spalding's .796 career winning percentage (from an era when teams played about once or twice a week) is the highest ever by a baseball pitcher, .058 ahead of Negro league star Dave Brown's .738.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Spalding was the first pitcher to reach 200 wins.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] In the months after signing for Chicago, Hulbert and Spalding organized the National League by enlisting the two major teams in the East and the four other top teams in what was then considered to be the West, also known as the jungle.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Joining Chicago initially were the leading teams from Cincinnati, Louisville, and St.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] The owners of these western clubs accompanied Hulbert and Spalding to New York where they secretly met with owners from New York City, Philadelphia, Hartford, and Boston.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Each signed the league's constitution, and the National League was officially born.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] "Spalding was thus involved in the transformation of baseball from a game of gentlemen athletes into a business and a professional sport." Although the National Association held on for a few more seasons, it was no longer recognized as the premier organization for professional baseball.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Gradually, it faded out of existence and was replaced by myriad minor leagues and associations around the country.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] In 1886, with Spalding as president of the franchise, the Chicago White Stockings (today's Chicago Cubs), began holding spring training in Hot Springs, Arkansas, which subsequently has been called the "birthplace" of spring training baseball.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] The location and the training concept was the brainchild of Spalding and his player/manager Cap Anson, who saw that the city and the natural springs created positives for their players.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] They first played in an area called the **Hot Springs Baseball Grounds**.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Many other teams followed the concept and began training in Hot Springs and other locations.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] In 1905, after Henry Chadwick wrote an article saying that baseball grew from the British sports of cricket and rounders, Spalding called for a commission to find out the real source of baseball.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] The commission called for citizens who knew anything about the founding of baseball to send in letters.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] After three years of searching, on December 30, 1907, Spalding received a letter that (erroneously) declared baseball to be the invention of Abner Doubleday.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] The commission was biased, as Spalding would not appoint anyone to the commission if they believed the sport was somewhat related to rounders or cricket.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Receiving the archives of Henry Chadwick in 1908, Spalding combined these records with his own memories (and biases) to write *America's National Game* (published 1911) which, despite its flaws, was probably the first scholarly account of the history of baseball.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] In 1876 while Spalding was playing and organizing the league, Spalding and his brother Walter began a sporting goods store in Chicago, which grew rapidly (14 stores by 1901) and expanded into a manufacturer and distributor of all kinds of sporting equipment.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] The company became "synonymous with sporting goods" and is still a going concern.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Spalding, from 1892 to 1941, sold books under the name Spalding Athletic Library on many different sports.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] In 1888–1889, Spalding took a group of major league players around the world to promote baseball and Spalding sporting goods.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] This was the first-ever world baseball tour.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Playing across the western U.S., the tour made stops in Hawaii (although no game was played), New Zealand, Australia, Ceylon, Egypt, Italy, France, and England.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] The tour returned to grand receptions in New York, Philadelphia, and Chicago.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] The tour included future Hall of Famers Cap Anson and John Montgomery Ward.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] The tour was also touted by Spalding as a launching point for baseball to reach the global stage.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] While Spalding and company gushed about their schlep around the world, waxing lyrical about baseball's future as a global sport, in reality, the tour had very little impact on the sport's hold overseas.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Sports like soccer, rugby, and cricket had already been established in many other countries due to the presence of European imperialism so baseball had a difficult time gaining popularity in these regions.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] While baseball did reach a wider global audience, it was due to a larger scale diffusion of the sport rather than the efforts of one magnate, like Spalding envisioned.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] While the players were on the tour, the National League instituted new rules regarding player pay that led to a revolt of players, led by Ward, who started the Players' League the following season (1890).
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] The league lasted one year, partially due to the anti-competitive tactics of Spalding to limit its success.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] The tour and formation of the Player's League is depicted in the 2015 movie *Deadball*.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] In 1900 Spalding was appointed by President McKinley as the USA's Commissioner at that year's Summer Olympic Games.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Spalding had been a prominent member of the Theosophical Society under William Quan Judge.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] In 1900, Spalding moved to San Diego having recently married his second wife, Elizabeth and became a prominent member and supporter of the Theosophical community Lomaland, which was being developed on Point Loma by Katherine Tingley.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] He built an estate in the Sunset Cliffs area of Point Loma where he lived with Elizabeth for the rest of his life.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] The Spaldings raised race horses and collected Chinese fine furniture and art.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] The Spaldings had an extensive library which included many volumes on Theosophy, art, and literature.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] In 1907–1909 he was the driving force behind the development of a paved road, known as the "Point Loma boulevard," from downtown San Diego to Point Loma and Ocean Beach; the road also provided good access to Lomaland.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] It later provided the basis for California State Route 209.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] He proposed the project, supervised it on behalf of the city, and paid a portion of the cost out of his own pocket.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] He joined with George Marston and other civic-minded businessmen to purchase the site of the original Presidio of San Diego, which they developed as a historic park and eventually donated to the city of San Diego.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] He ran unsuccessfully for the United States Senate in 1911 as a Republican, but lost to eventual winner John D.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Works by a vote of 92–21 in the California legislature.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] He helped to organize the 1915 Panama–California Exposition, serving as second vice-president.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] He died of a stroke on September 9, 1915, in San Diego, one week after his 66th birthday.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] His ashes were scattered at his request.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] He was elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame by the Veterans Committee in 1939, as one of the first inductees from the 19th century at that summer's opening ceremonies.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] His plaque in the Hall of Fame reads "Albert Goodwill Spalding.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Organizational genius of baseball's pioneer days.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] Star pitcher of Forest City Club in late 1860s, 4-year champion Bostons 1871–75 and manager-pitcher of champion Chicagos in National League's first year.
[src:baseball-glove/albert-spalding] His nephew, also named Albert Spalding, was a renowned violinist.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] In baseball, an **appeal play** occurs when a member of the defensive team calls the attention of an umpire to an infraction that they would otherwise ignore.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] To properly execute a live ball appeal, a fielder must, with a live ball, tag the runner or base in question and communicate to the umpire what the infraction was and which runner committed the infraction.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] Such communication may be non-verbal, implicit, or assumed—so long as the intent of the fielder is clear to the umpire.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] Contrary to popular belief, an appeal out is not a force out unless it is regarding a missed force base.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] For example, if a runner from third base tags up and scores, but a runner from second base leaves too early, failing to tag up, and then is put out on the appeal, the run counts if it was scored before the appeal by the fielders.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] Rare situations with a viable appeal on a runner who misses his force base require the umpire to recognize an apparent fourth out.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] Umpires will only rule on legal appeals.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] A potential appeal is *viable* if the appeal is legal and the umpire knows that the runner has indeed committed an infraction and will be called out if the appeal is executed by a fielder.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] Suppose that runners are on first and third base, and the batter hits a fly ball.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] The runner on third tags up, leaving third base immediately after the outfielder touches the ball.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] The runner seems to score, beating the throw home, but failing to touch home plate.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] The runner proceeds into his dugout without again attempting to touch home base.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] The runner on first base stays at first base, and action becomes relaxed while the ball is in the infield.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] The fielders now suspect that the runner left third base too early and also missed the plate.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] Suppose then that a fielder, with the live ball, touches home base and says to the nearest umpire, "I think they never touched home." This is a legal and viable appeal, and so the umpire should call the runner out and direct that his run shall not count.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] Since the ball was live (and indeed must be for appeals to be legal), the runner from first could have attempted to advance at any time during the appeals.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] If the defense attempts to play on that runner, their opportunity to appeal the runner from third base is lost, and the run would count regardless of any subsequent attempt to appeal.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] A member of the defensive team may appeal to the umpire when a batter bats out of turn.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] The umpire then enforces the penalty for batting out of turn, if any.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] The ball must be live for this as for any appeal.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] After the appeal is made, the umpire will usually signal "Time" and figure out whether the appeal is successful.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] The field umpire then signals whether the batter swung, and such a judgment must, by rule, prevail.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] The umpire asked is usually the first-base umpire (or third-base, if the batter is left-handed).
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] The plate umpire is not required to ask for assistance if they believe the request is making a farce of the game.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] If the bat barely left the shoulder of the batter and the catcher appeals the "no-swing" call, the umpire will probably deny the appeal.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] This procedure was introduced because it is commonplace for a plate umpire to be unable to see some swings.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] A manager may ask an umpire to request assistance on other plays where another umpire had a better view, but the umpire is not required to do so.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] Such requests are common when a close home run or foul ball call is disputed, or when determining the accuracy of a close catch or no catch call.
[src:baseball-glove/appeal-play] In such a case, the plate umpire would put a new ball in play, and after the ball became live by rule, the defense could appeal the missed base.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] In baseball, an **assist** (denoted by **A**) is a defensive statistic, baseball being one of the few sports in which the *defensive* team controls the ball.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] An assist is credited to every defensive player who fields or touches the ball (after it has been hit by the batter) prior to the recording of a putout, even if the contact was unintentional.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] For example, if a ball strikes a player's leg and bounces off him to another fielder, who tags the baserunner, the first player is credited with an assist.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] A fielder can receive a maximum of one assist per out recorded.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] An assist is also credited if a putout would have occurred, had another fielder not committed an error.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] For example, a shortstop might field a ground ball cleanly, but the first baseman might drop his throw.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] In this case, an error would be charged to the first baseman, and the shortstop would be credited with an assist.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] If a pitcher records a strikeout where the third strike is caught by the catcher, the pitcher is not credited with an assist.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] However, if the batter becomes a baserunner on a dropped third strike and the pitcher is involved in recording a putout by fielding the ball and either tagging the runner out or throwing to first base for the out, the pitcher is credited with an assist just as any other fielder would be.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] Assists are an important statistic for outfielders, as a play often occurs when a baserunner on the opposing team attempts to advance on the basepaths when the ball is hit to the outfield (even on a caught fly ball that results in an out; see tag up).
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] It is the outfielder's job to field the ball and make an accurate throw to another fielder who is covering the base before the runner reaches it.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] The fielder then attempts to tag the runner out.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] This is especially important if the runner was trying to reach home plate, as the assist and tag prevent the baserunner from scoring a run.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] Assists are much rarer for outfielders than infielders (with the exception of first basemen) because the play is harder to make, and also because outfielder assist situations occur less often than the traditional ground-ball assist for a shortstop, second baseman, or third baseman.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] However, as a result, outfield assists are worth far more than infield assists, and tell more about an outfielder's throwing arm than infielder assists do.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] In recent years, some sabermetricians have begun referring to assists by outfielders as **baserunner kills**.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] Some sabermetricians are also using *baserunner holds* as a statistic to measure outfield arms.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] A baserunner hold occurs when the baserunner does not attempt to advance an extra base on an outfielder out of concern of being thrown out by a strong, accurate throw.
[src:baseball-glove/assist-baseball] This can be combined with baserunner kills for better accuracy, as runners often do not try for an extra base when an outfielder with an excellent arm is playing.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] A **baseball glove** or **mitt** is a large glove worn by baseball players of the defending team, which assists players in catching and fielding balls hit by a batter or thrown by a teammate.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Gloves are traditionally made of leather, but today other options exist, such as PVC and synthetic leather.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] By convention, the glove is described by the handedness of the intended wearer, rather than the hand on which the glove is worn: a glove that fits on the left hand—used by a right-handed thrower—is called a *right-handed* (RH) or "right-hand throw" (RHT) glove.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Conversely, a left-handed glove (LH or LHT) is worn on the right hand, allowing the player to throw the ball with the left hand.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Early baseball was a game played without gloves.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] During the gradual transition to gloves, a player who continued to play without one was called a *barehanded catcher;* this did not refer to the position of catcher, but rather to the practice of catching with bare hands.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] The earliest glove was not webbed and not particularly well suited for catching but was used more to swat a ball to the ground so that it could be picked up.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] One of the first players believed to have used a baseball glove was Doug Allison, a catcher for the Cincinnati Red Stockings, in 1870, due to an injured left hand.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] The first confirmed glove use was by Charlie Waitt, a St.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Louis outfielder and first baseman who, in 1875, donned a pair of flesh-colored gloves.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Glove use slowly caught on as more and more players began using different forms of gloves.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Many early baseball gloves were simple leather gloves with the fingertips cut off, supposedly to allow for the same control of a bare hand but with extra padding.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] For the first two decades of professional baseball, these types of gloves were worn primarily by catchers, who sustained frequent hand injuries to such a point that duties for catching typically alternated each day at a time when field positions did not carry backups.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] The catcher's mitt, a glove designed to be much larger than the hand and to cover it entirely, were offered for sale for the first time in 1890.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Pitcher, first baseman and outfielder Albert Spalding, originally skeptical of glove use, influenced more infielders to begin using gloves.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Spalding later founded the sporting goods company Spalding, which still manufactures baseball gloves, along with other sports equipment.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] By the mid-1890s, it was normal for players to wear gloves in the field.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] In the early 1900s baseball glove manufacturers started experimenting with a "full web" or "web-pocketed" gloves, gloves with a small 0.5" ~ 1" piece of leather connecting the thumb and index finger.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Unlike current webbing, this was often made of a single piece of leather fully connected to both fingers of the glove, not with strips of leather connecting both sides of the glove as would be seen starting in the 1920s.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] In 1920, Bill Doak, a pitcher for the St.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Louis Cardinals, suggested that a web be placed between the first finger and the thumb in order to create a pocket.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] This design soon became the standard for baseball gloves.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Doak patented his design and sold it to Rawlings.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] His design became the precursor to modern gloves and enabled Rawlings to become the preferred glove of professional players.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] For many years, it was customary for fielders to leave their gloves on the field when their team went in to bat.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] This practice was prohibited by the major leagues in 1954.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Baseball gloves have grown progressively larger since their inception.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] While catching in baseball had always been two-handed, gloves eventually grew to a size that made it easier to catch the ball in the webbing of the glove, using the off-hand to keep the ball from falling out.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] A glove is typically worn on the non-dominant hand, leaving the dominant hand for the more strenuous and precise task of throwing the ball; for example, a right-handed player would wear a glove on their left hand, which would still be referred to as a "right handed glove".
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] The shape and size of the baseball glove are governed by official baseball rules.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Section 3.00 - Equipment and Uniforms specifies glove dimensions and materials in parts 3.04 through 3.07.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] The structure and quality of the baseball glove have developed greatly over the past century.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Today, the production of baseball gloves is much more precise and efficient.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] This has greatly increased the usefulness and accessibility of baseball gloves to the general population.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Currently, Easton is "experimenting with combining leather and Kevlar (used in bullet-proof vests) in a new ultra-lightweight glove line".
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Manufacturers have also designed new, non-traditional types of gloves to suit non-traditional players.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Also, manufacturers are personalizing gloves for high-caliber players to help increase their exposure on national television.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Although there have been numerous advances in baseball glove design, the greatest arguably came with the advent of the catcher's mitt.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Yet despite state-of-the-art mitts being used by catchers, a Wake Forest University study of 36 U.S. minor-league players demonstrated that the mitts did not offer enough protection from hand and wrist injuries.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] The highest-quality baseball gloves are typically made of heavy leather.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] These leather gloves usually take more time for the player to break in.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] They also provide a tighter, more personalized fit for the player.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] This is an improvement from youth and recreational gloves, which tend to feature palm pads and/or adjustable Velcro wrist straps.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] These gloves take less time to break in or are pre-broken in, are less personal and more "one size fits all".
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Baseball gloves are measured by starting at the top of the index finger of the glove and measuring down the finger, along the inside of the pocket and then out to the heel of the glove.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Gloves typically range in size from 9 inches (229 mm) (youth starter size) to 12+3⁄4 inches (324 mm) for adult outfield play.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] Catcher's mitts, unlike those of other gloves, are measured around the circumference, and they typically have 32-to-34-inch (813–864 mm) patterns.
[src:baseball-glove/baseball-glove] The shape and size of a glove are described by its pattern.
